Identification of Marker Genes Across Multiple Datasets

Elif Ayse Ozcan

24 03 2021

Abstract

The increasing amount of RNA-seq data from independent studies are combined to assess the studies’ statistical significance of medical questions. Therefore, meta-analysis, in which relevant but independent studies are gathered to form one large data, has become a highly popular method for analysis in medical reports. In this protocol, meta-analysis is used to assess the transcriptional differences in a subset of CD8+ T cells, particularly exhausted CD8+ T cells known to lose the proper cytotoxic T cell functioning in long-term exposure to viral infection occurs. Four datasets examining exhaustion in CD8+ T cells are collected and combined to determine the transcriptome of the exhaustion in a precise and accurate manner.

Introduction

CD8+ T cells, also known as cytotoxic T cells, maintain adaptive immunity via killing intracellular pathogens and tumors. In the effector state in which T cells actively function in killing infected cells. After the removal of infected cells, most of these functional effector T cells die except a small number of them enter a quiescent state and become memory T cells. The memory T cells downregulate the effector molecules required for the proper effector T cell functioning and enter a stem-like proliferation state. Although memory T cells remain quiescent, they still keep to the ability to reactivate the effector state and proliferation by upregulating the effector molecules upon recognizing the same antigen. However, in chronic diseases such as cancer or viral infection, CD8+ T cells are exposed to long-term antigen and inflammatory signals which inhibit T cell activity and cause memory T cells to enter into a state called ‘exhaustion’. The major characteristics of the exhausted CD8+ T cells are diminished cytokine production, decreased survival rate, and the increased expression of inhibitory receptors such as PD-1, CTLA-4, lymphocyte-activation gene 3 (LAG3), T cell immunoglobulin domain, and mucin domain 3 (Tim-3), CD244, CD160, T cell immunoreceptor (TIGIT). [1] The other effects of the prolonged antigen and inflammation effects seen in CD8+T cells include the lack of antigen-independent homeostasis, changes in homing and migration, changes in cytokine and chemokine receptor expression, altered metabolism, and an altered transcriptional program with specific transcription factors. The research about the exhausted CD8+ T cells is growing each day since if the process causes exhaustion is well known, this exhaustion state could be reversed and this could be useful in cancer and chronic viral infection treatments. For instance, the discovery of the PD-1 receptor pathway has led now to the production of PD-1 blockade drugs against cancer which also means that a subset of the exhausted cell could be converted to their effector state. Comparative transcriptional analysis between naive, effector, memory, and exhausted T cell suggested that exhausted T cells possess a unique transcriptional pattern. Even though the inhibitory receptors in exhausted T cells are known, our knowledge on how to reverse the exhausted state remains incomplete. Therefore, transcriptional profiling of exhausted T cells would give an idea of how this process occurs and could be manipulated to convert the exhausted state. Meta-analysis is a quantitative and statistical approach to assess the results of a variety of independent researches which studies the same or similar questions. A meta-analysis combines the results of these different researches to give a more precise conclusion about the results of these questions. Since the analysis uses more than one research and integrates the researches from unrelated sources, it gives a more accurate conclusion compared to a single study. The inclusion of different datasets and how relatable these datasets are to the question of interest are decisive factors in the analysis. And if these requirements are met, this systematic review by the meta-analysis would increase the strength of the results and the conclusion derived from that. Therefore, the quality of the individual researches is important to consider and literature research or in some cases aggregated data could be used in the analysis. Another crucial point is the homogeneity among studies. Because the differences coming from the variability of intervention effects lead to statistical heterogeneity which causes inaccurate and misguided conclusions in the meta-analysis. Thus, the lesser heterogeneity between studies results in lesser biases and this helps to arrive at more meaningful conclusions.[2]In this protocol, we examined the RNA-seq results of four different datasets exhausted CD8+ T cell populations individually and then performed a meta-analysis on these datasets to have a more systematic view and to obtain more precise results about the transcription profile of exhaustion. Meta-analysis provides us a reproducible and reliable result by minimizing the bias.

Results

The first and the main data to be examined is taken from Gene Expression Omnibus with the accession number of GSE150120. The RNA-seq raw counts are obtained from CD8+T cells in different states and the counts are examined for the differentially expressed genes. The experiment for the RNA-seq includes OT-I CD45.1+ mice on the C57BL6/J background and CD8+ T cells are isolated from the spleens of these OT-I mice with negative selection and magnetic beads. The purified CD8+ T cells are stimulated with 10ng/ml OVA(257-264) peptide for 5 days with the presence of IL-15 and IL-7 in the cell culture to produce exhausted CD8+ T cells. For the controls, purified CD8+T cells either didn’t receive any peptides or stimulated with OVA(257-264) peptide once for only 2 days with the presence of IL-15 and IL-7. Cells that did not receive any peptide stimulation are considered naive while the cells stimulated with the OVA peptide for only two days are regarded as effector T cells as they are stimulated for a short period of time. On the 5th day, all the cells from three culture conditions are collected and RNA-Seq is performed. Before the differential gene expression analysis, principal component analysis(PCA) is performed to reduce dimensions in the raw data to determine any outliers and have a quick check to count data obtained. In Figure 1A., the PCA results are shown in a graph for each biological replicates and each condition used in the experiment. PCA graph confirms that the cells are grouped according to the different conditions they are treated with. There is no need for rearrangement of counts as there are no outliers and most of the variation is on PC1 as expected. Next, differential expression analysis is performed with DESeq2 package from Bioconductor to identify differentially expressed genes between CD8+ T cells repeatedly stimulated with OVA peptide and the cells only one time stimulated with the peptide. The results of the DESeq2 analysis are shown in Figure 1B. as a MA plot(Bland-Altman plot) with the Nod1 gene indicated on the plot as the lowest adjusted p-value. Nod1 gene encodes nucleotide-binding and oligomerization domain (NOD)-like receptors (NLRs) which are a family of intracellular sensors that have key roles in innate immunity and inflammation.[3] Also known as the mean-difference plot, the MA plot gives an overview of how different conditions affect genes. The log2 fold change of genes between repeatedly stimulated and one-time stimulated cell counts are plotted on the y-axis while an average of the normalized counts is plotted on the x-axis[4]. From the MA plot, it is observed that the Nod1 gene has a log fold change of around -5. The Nod1 gene is significantly downregulated in repeatedly stimulated cells compared to one-time stimulated cells almost 32 times.

Figure 1.RNA-Seq analysis A.Dimension reduction plot of RNA-Seq result which shows that the cells from same cultures cluster together while different cultures cluster away from each other. There is no outliers considering the plot. B.MA plot showing the mean variance and the lowest adjusted p-value is labeled on the plot as Nod1 gene. Each gene is plotted as a dot. Genes having an adjusted p-value below a threshold of 0.1 is depicted as red. Black line indicates the difference between upregulated and down regulated genes.

DESeq2 package used to determine the differential gene expression in repeated and single peptide stimulated CD8+T cells that form effector and exhausted CD8+T cells, respectively. DESeq2 uses the raw counts directly and normalizes the counts internally by calculating a geometric mean for all genes across all samples. Next, the counts in each gene are divided by this geometric mean. DESeq2 is a popular method to examine bulk RNA-seq analysis and it corrects for the library size and RNA composition bias.[5] The genes having no count in any of the samples are removed to eliminate genes without any contribution to the analysis. After DESeq2 is performed, from the 52.459 genes obtained from RNA-seq analysis, 5300 genes are found to be upregulated while 5064 genes are found to be downregulated when the repeatedly stimulated CD8+T cells,i.e exhausted cells, compared to only one time stimulated ones, effector cells, The results are first examined in Figure 2. with a heatmap displaying the 30 genes having the highest variance across the samples. There is a certain difference between the set of genes depending on the conditions in the heatmap. The condition with repeated peptide stimulation showed the highest variance in a certain set of genes such as Lag3, Cd80, Maats1, and Gzmb. However, the genes with the highest variance in the repeated stimulation, i.e exhausted cells, are found to have lower variance in the other two conditions. Moreover, according to the heatmap in Figure 2., the genes in the one-time stimulated cells and not stimulated cells display similar variance patterns to each other but not to the repeatedly stimulated cells.

Gene Ontology Enrichment Analysis

The gene ontology enrichment analysis is performed on the data to seek the significant biological processes contributing to the exhaustion state in T cells. In Table 1., 10 GO terms with the most significant p-value obtained from Fisher’s test are listed. Both classic and Elim algorithms are used to assess the most significant and relevant GO terms. In the classic algorithm, 4 out of 10 most significant terms are related to T cells and their regulation or regulation of inflammatory response in the biological process of GO data. Some of these GO terms include positive regulation of T cell differentiation and lymphocyte differentiation. When the Elim algorithm alone is used in the gene ontology analysis, regulation of alpha-beta T cell proliferation, isotype switching, cellular response to interferon-gamma are found to be significant as shown in the table below.

These genes greatly affect functional effector T cell to enter exhaustion state and lose its functionality.

Correlation Results

Differential gene expression analysis and gene ontology enrichment analysis give us an idea of how the exhaustion state differs from the functional effector state. However, there is still a need to check the results and genes by comparing other datasets so that more relevant and consistent results could be obtained. Moreover, the biases would be minimized with the larger dataset. So, there are three more datasets that also investigate the exhausted T cells transcriptome with bulk RNA-seq. The first of the dataset could be accessed from GEO with GSE132984. The experiment uses the Tox transcription factor which is an important exhaustion regulator in CD8+ T cells when its expression is increased. TOX is known to play a main role in the exhaustion induction in the CD8+T cells, therefore in this study the transcriptional profile of wildtype P14 T cells are compared with the TOX-/- mutant P14 T cells which are produced by transduction of TOX-encoding retrovirus following 8 days of Cl-13 infection. Due to the TOX gene’s fundamental role in leading to the exhaustion state, two CD8+ T cell populations are created with wildtype and mutant in which wildtype forms an exhausted CD8+ T cell population while the mutant forms a non-exhausted CD8+ T cell population. RNA-Seq data is used to compare the transcriptional features of the exhausted CD8+ T cells and to find the differentially expressed genes in this dataset. Later, log fold change and stat values for the first highest 100 genes are selected from the results of this experiment and the previous experiment, and a correlation analysis is performed to measure the linear correlation between them via Pearson’s correlation.

Figure 5. Correlation plot of GSE132984 and GSE150120 are shown. A. Log2 fold change is compared between these datasets with the Pearson’s correlation method. The fisrt 100 genes with the highest log2 fold change are chosen for both of the dataset. B. Stat values are compared between these dataset with the Pearson’s correlation method. The fisrt 100 genes with the highest stat values are chosen for both of the dataset.(p<2e-16)

Figure 5. depicts the correlation plots of the log2 fold changes and stat values of the genes, respectively. Log2 fold change corresponds to the logarithmic change of the gene expressions between the effector and the exhausted states while stat values respond to the Wald test statistics which comes with the DESeq2 package. The Wald test evaluates the null hypothesis under a set of parameters. The Wald test calculates how far the parameters are from zero. The closer to zero, the Wald test fails to reject the null hypothesis.[17] According to the plots in Figure 5., both log fold change and statistics from both datasets are positively correlated to each other with a correlation coefficient of 0.9. The log fold change is almost 20 times more in the GSE150120 data while it only changes to 6 times fold in GSE132984 in Figure 5.A. The correlation of Wald statistics plot in Figure 5.B also shows a similar difference in which the stat value of GSE150120 is up to 30 while the same value is three times smaller in GSE132984. Even though there is an outlier stat value in the plot, the plot shows that the stat values of both datasets are highly correlated positively.

After the correlation analysis, another data again studying the transcriptome of exhaustion in CD8+ T cell is added. This third data included in the report has an access number of GSE93006. In this set of experiments, C57BL/6 mice are injected with B16-OVA, a melanoma cell line to produce exhausted cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs). Furthermore, a low number of OT-I tumor-specific CD8+ T cells are injected into the tumor-bearing mice together with P-14 CD8+ T cells which, on the contrary to OT-I cells, are tumor-ignorant. Therefore, the melanoma tumor in the mice causes OT-I tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes (TILs) to become exhausted after 8 days whereas the tumor-ignorant P-14 TILs don’t interact with the tumor cells and maintain the effector T cell features. The results from the differential gene expression are again plotted against our main data (GSE150120) to check for correlation.

Meta-Analysis

In fundamental part of the analysis is to combine all the datasets examined previously to perform a meta-analysis. With the meta-analysis, the more precise and accurate genes that are relevant to exhausted CD8+ T cells transcriptome could be determined. Meta-analysis results in two tests called Fisher’s and Stouffer’s which are required to combine p-values with different statistical properties.[6] It has been proven that combining p-values from independent studies for multiple hypothesis testing lowers the Type I error and there is no consistently most powerful test. Therefore, combining the p-values and comparing different tests would be helpful. For example, Fisher’s test is more robust than the z-test, however, having the same effect sizes makes the z-test more powerful than Fisher’s test.[7] Considering these reasons, both Fisher’s and Stouffer’s tests are used in this meta-analysis.

Meta-analysis of all four RNA-Seq data displays 3937 and 3679 upregulated genes in Fisher’s and Stouffer’s tests, respectively. However, it has been found that only 56 and 146 genes are downregulated significantly according to these tests. The heatmaps in Figure 8. show 30 genes with the lowest p-values in both of the tests so that the differences between the tests could be observed as well as the gene varieties.

Discussion

Exhaustion in CD8+ T cells is first examined in the separate studies starting with the study whose GEO accession number is GSE150120. Differentially expressed genes in this study are shown in Figures 1. and 2. When the repeatedly stimulated cells are compared to one-time stimulated cells, the Nod1 gene is appeared to be greatly decreased in expression. This confirms the experimental conditions of the study. The repeatedly stimulated cells represent exhausted CD8+ T cells while the one-time stimulated cells represent effector CD8+ T cells. Nod1 gene encodes for Nod1 protein which is a pattern recognition receptor for viral and bacterial pathogens and Nod1 protein is known to initiate inflammation and immune response. Moreover, the lacking of Nod1 receptors drives primed T cells into even cell death.[11] The decrease in Nod1 gene expression is due to the diminished capacity of exhausted cells to recognize pathogen-associated molecular patterns and their reduced effector capabilities. The heatmap in Figure 2. shows how the variance among genes in each T cell population differs. The genes showing a high variance in the exhausted, repeatedly stimulated, cells, do not show great variance in effector, one time stimulated, cells or naive, not stimulated, cells. However, the variance pattern in the effector and naive CD8+ T cells is observed to follow a similar pattern. Therefore, it could be elicited that the transcription profile of the exhaustion state is greatly different than the naive or effector T cell states.

Gene enrichment ontology analysis enables to obtain biological processes contributing to the exhaustion state in T cells rather than only genes. The gene ontology results from Table 1. and Figure 3. proves that the differentially expressed genes between the effector and exhausted CD8+ T cells contribute to the biological processes in exhaustion. The significant GO terms are related to T cell processes such as proliferation and differentiation. The acyclic graph reveals that the positive regulation of cell-cell adhesion, response to stress, cellular macromolecule biosynthetic process, and regulation of T cell activation are some of the significant biological processes to contribute to the analysis. Exhausted CD8+ T cells are mostly known for their expression of inhibitory receptors on their surfaces which is also observed in the gene ontology results as the positive regulation of cell-cell adhesion annotation contains some of the inhibitory receptors. The annotation of the stress response is also related to the exhaustion state in which T cells further might go into physical deletion.[12]

Meta-analysis is an important method to gather information from several studies and draw a conclusion from their combination. The meta-analysis provides a greater statistical significance compared to any of the individual studies since the analysis benefits from the larger number of samples and the variation among samples. Therefore, different RNA-seq results investigating the exhaustion state of CD8+ T cells are combined to create one large data pool which infers the true significant results. During the meta-analysis, p-value based methods, Fisher’s probability, and Stouffer’s Z-test are practiced. While Fisher’s probability is more sensitive to the low p-values, Stouffer’s test takes into account the weighting by the sample size. This difference is seen in the heatmaps in Figure 8. The genes that appeared to be significant in the heatmaps are involved in the exhaustion of CD8+ T cells as expected such as Gzmb which encodes for granzyme B found in cytotoxic T cells is highly expressed in exhausted CD8+ T cells.[13] However, some genes are not expected to be significant such as Maats1 which encodes cilia and flagella-associated protein and regulates motility during spermatogenesis.[14] Since the Maats1 gene does not play a role in the immune system or exhaustion of T cells, it could be regarded as an outlier.

One of the important results of the meta-analysis is the number of significantly upregulated and downregulated genes. The upregulated gene number is 70 times more than the downregulated gene number in Fisher’s test while this difference in number is decreased to 25 in Stouffer’test. The reason why there are so few downregulated genes might reflect the exhaustion state of CD8+ T cells. Because the exhaustion state is not a quiescent state where the CD8+ T cells remain inactive and transcriptionally silent but rather a lot of negative regulatory receptor is transcribed. And before the exhaustion state, T cells enter the memory state in which they remain quiescent.[15] The unbalance between the gene number could be explained by that or there could be other reasons for this unbalance such as the high heterogeneity and variance between studies or the usage of inappropriate studies or the inadequate data addition to meta-analysis.[16] These drawbacks could be overcome with the larger sample size and inclusion of more RNA-seq data.

Next, the meta-analysis results are compared to each RNA-seq data individually to depict the study’s role in the meta-analysis and observe the intersection between them. In the Venn diagrams in Figures 9. and 10., the meta-analysis results are compared with the results of the individual studies. While the DESeq2 method is used to determine differential gene expression in individual datasets, NOISeq is used in the meta-analysis due to its effectiveness against the bias that comes from read size effect. Because meta-analysis makes use of a variety of data with an uneven number of read size which causes the analysis to detect incorrect genes as differentially expressed. NOISeq eliminates this bias of read size effect between the studies. However, this could be some minor changes between the individual study analysis and meta-analysis since different methods like DESeq2 and NOISeq are used.

The Venn diagrams in Figure 9. point to the heterogeneity among the datasets. Because there are only 4 genes detected to be significantly upregulated by all four independent datasets. While this number is too low considering the thousand of upregulated genes in each dataset. This difference could be due to the dataset GSE132984 in which the CD8+ T cells are compared from wild-type mice and Tox knock-out mice. Tox is a known exhaustion marker in cytotoxic cells however, only knocking-out Tox could not reverse all the other exhaustion markers. Thus, we observe that the GSE132984 dataset does not share genes as much as with the other datasets. That’s why in the second Venn diagram in Figure 9.B, GSE132984 is excluded and the differential gene expression results of the other datasets are compared to meta-analysis. This diagram shows a higher number of shared genes between the datasets and meta-analysis which could be inferred as the heterogeneity comes from the GSE132984. However, this is not the case when the downregulated genes are compared. First of all, there are more genes are found to be downregulated in the intersection of the results of datasets. And when the datasets are compared with meta-analysis, this time GSE132984 datasets are observed to contribute to the diagram more, and all the datasets except GSE88987 and the meta-analysis share 3 significantly downregulated genes.

In conclusion, meta-analysis is highly crucial in high-throughput data analysis and very useful for determining significant genes that have an effect of exhaustion in CD8+ T cells. The addition of relevant experiments and their RNA-seq data could be combined to the meta-analysis to have a larger pool of samples and minimize the bias as long as the homogeneity is maintained among the studies. Combining more datasets to the meta-analysis could help to detect more exhaustion-related genes and inferring the transcriptional differences between cytotoxic T cell subsets.

Methods

Statistics were done using R 4.0.0. In addition metaSeq(v3.10; Tsuyuzaki&Nikaido, 2019), DESeq2(v3.12; Love, 2014), ggplot2(v3.3.3; Wickham, 2020) and topGO(v3.12; Alexa, 2020) packages are used.

Data Availability

The raw count datasets of the RNA-Seq results are provided with Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO). Accession numbers of the datasets used in the paper are GSE150120, GSE132984, GSE93006 and GSE88987.
